\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Now let me think. I think I had - a penny a week when 
I was half time at school - at work. Then I was earning - after we got the apprenticeship served at twelve month you was earning about five shillings per week, four shillings one week and six shillings the next. Because you realize if you were working in 
t
he morning turn we worked more hours than we did the afternoon turn, see. It varied - well it averaged ten shillings a fortnight. I think I'd a penny. Then when I became full time we got ten shillings. This is my case, I don't know about the others. We go
t
 ten shillings and me mother gave me threepence a week spending money. Out of ten shillings. Now I got promoted from one job to another in the mill and it was ten and sixpence was that. I got a sixpenny rise. So me mother said I could keep the sixpence sp
e
nding money and she'd have threepence more, I'd have threepence more spending money. See what I mean, so I got sixpence. Then - I'd be twelve years of age then. And I've been all over. I've been in South Africa, I've been in Greece for seven years, I live
d in Greece seven years. I've been all over and that was the biggest rise in spending money I ever had in my life. Was that threepence to sixpence it was the biggest lift I ever had. It seemed to be.
