\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did they ever have games, card games or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh no. No, no. No, just talk - purely and simply. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 You know how people divide society into different social classes, in the ti
me before 1918 did you think of some people as belonging to one social class and others to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
Well I don't know. I used to think so. I would think so at one time. But I'll tell you what - I'll tell you what routed me more than anything. When th
e 1914 war broke out, my two brothers went off right away and I used to go to church that day, 1914, you see I was twenty-two then. I used to go to church and the parson said one Sunday that all the young people, you know, all the young boys and that sort
 
of thing of age should enlist. Not in as many words but he - he gave you style, understand that. And he had two sons as well. So I thought if I've got to go why can't his. Then you get a bit of class distinction then don't you, 'cos he was a vicar. I thin
k
 he had plenty of money. He had plenty of money. And for him wanting to send someone else to do a job - to look after his money, look after his property and that sort of thing, it didn't seem right to me. I just thought, what have I to defend. Nothing but
 myself. You see what I mean. I went later. But it just - got your back, up a little bit then you know. I never went - I never went to church much after that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What did you think the different social classes consisted of, how did you view it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
Well there was no question about it you know that in the old days there'd be children were exploited. There's no question about that is there. When I had to go into the mill for eighteenpence a week. You know what I mean, you don't think much about it as 
a
 kid but as they grow older you do. I go - I go to work - a fortnight for nothing and eighteenpence. And then you got a threepence a month rise. Well they're starting these children now at fifteen that've never been anywhere with seven and eight pounds a 
week. You see the difference in the scale. That's why - we get a little bit impatient with older people get a bit impatient with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid857016\charrsid11084748 youngsters}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  - younger ones, to me, because they - they've no idea. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid857016\charrsid11084748 Now when all's said and done, England were built up out of
 the industrial revelation you know when all these - when all these mills were going up and one thing and another you know. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
There were millions of pounds made up here, I think - I think many a time - in 1911 I believe it was Mr Buckmaster put up as M.P. for Keighley against a man called Anderson who was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid857016\charrsid11084748 Socialist
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 . }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid857016\charrsid11084748 
And bear in mind Anderson had a very, very strong character, I always remember that as a kid, I was only 1911 so you can tell how old I was, I was only nineteen. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
I used to go to these meetings and - I just listened to Buckmaster talking and this Anderson, and he could carry a crowd could Anderson, you know what I mean. He could - oh - follow him. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid857016\charrsid11084748 
I thought, this fellows going to get in and Buckmaster, he was a Queen's Councillor I believe at the time, he was a barrister, something like that, big man. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 He'd been in Parliament before, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid857016\charrsid11084748 in fact}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
 he finished up Lord Buckmaster. There's a man called Money, Keels and Money came up to speak for Buckmaster at that election and Money was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid857016\charrsid11084748 reckoned}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  to be the be
st economist in England and he was speaking about Keighley and district you know, speaking for Buckmaster. And he spoke about the Worth Valley. And the Worth Valley stretches from Keighley to Oxenhope, you know where you are Oxenhope, it's higher up than 
Haworth, that - that line - railway line, it's a private line now, that's only the use of. And he said that Valley was the richest valley in England. The richest valley}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid857016\charrsid11084748  in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  England. There were half the Bradford manufacturers lived up there, all the Keighley 
mill owners lived up there nearly, right up that valley. And I've looked at this since, I've worked for them since, plenty of them, I've been in their houses, I know them, and they built it all out of slate, well - I won't say slave labour, very near it. 
The Industrial Revolution - the Industrial time you know, revolution came on. Admitted you got the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 Luddites}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
 and that sort of thing that broke the machinery up in that - those days and that sort of thing because they thought they were going to be out of wo
rk. And all that sort of thing, but we found out later there's a demand for these things and you can carry on with it with the machinery. But when you think you were knocking about at eighteenpence a week, you'd a penny spending money. And as you got }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 on}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 , as I say I used to go to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 night school}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  three nights a week. Well there'd be a plenty of these wealthy people's sons up the valley there come to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 night school}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  at Keighley. The evening classes, you see what I mean, to learn the same subject as ourselves. Th
en I was in the textile trade you see, that was it. And used to meet these fellows. And you know what it is after you come out of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 night school}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 , come on let's have a bit of a door - we'd a dodge a night some night, you know what I mean, you know, went out t
o Bingley or something like that. Well deary me these fellows had shillings to me pence, I couldn't go with these fellows.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Then one chap - I always one chap saying his father had given him his spending money that night, that was once - Thursday, he'
d given him half a sovereign. That was his spending money for the week. He'd be a chap perhaps a couple of years older than me. And I - I don't think I had threepence. And it doesn't - it doesn't go down right with somebody like that, bear in mind, I know
 
- if I had a hundred thousand pound and two youngsters I should want those two youngsters to have that hundred thousand pound, I'm not saying that but for a moment if I was in there place. But my idea was when you've got to get out of rut - or you're goin
g
 to be where you are all your life. So of course you get - you get - you've got to get stuck into it, do it that's all. But you never had that further education you know. We only had the ordinary elementary education. I never got to go to the grammar scho
ol here. You see, what I mean, all these fellows had been to the grammar school, I'd been working in the mill. Like talking in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 night school}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  about the working and the stuff I could beat them at i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
. You see, I'd had a couple of years, they were only just learning. But I know what best and of stick. I've been with them scores of times since then you know, what they make of these fellows.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What sort of people lived in the district where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh quite reasonable - ordinary working people. Quite reasonable people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Would you describe it as a working class district?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes, I think so, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What sort of people were they, were they all much alike?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Very much. Oh very much -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Or were there wide variations in standards of living?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
Well perhaps - we should be - well with a crowd like ours you know what I mean, as we - we were worse off than most of them you know. You'd often see these fellows that you play with and all that sort of thing and as you say, at Easter or Whi
tsun time, if that was the day for a new suit they'd have a new suit. I couldn't. Hadn't one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Were some of the families thought of as rough and some as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh yes. Yes, but we didn't get many of them where we were. No, they weren't too bad. Weren't too much - they went on much as we did.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Would any group feel itself superior to the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 I don't - don't think - only that could fight better that was all. If you were going to be fi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 gh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 ter}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 , they}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
 thought they was top-notches.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 C
an you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from another, were there some people that you had to be specially respectful to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 No, not - no, that's right, just one or two old lady }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 spinsters}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  there about, you know what I mean
, you see around. It were only just to say Miss Butt and Miss So and So. You know what I mean, and you always respected Miss Butt although - she'd say good morning, that was all, you know what I mean, that'd be about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Was there anybody that you called sir or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
No, your teachers at school you had to do. And when you went to a factory or anything like that if the - boss or his son came through - it was sir you know or - Mr Jacks perhaps or Mr so and so, you know what I mean, used to just sa
y that. Just a matter of giving them their place in the field where they were, you wee what I mean, the - factory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 In the district where you lived who would be considered to be the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Well I should say the Mayor. Not where we
 lived. He didn't live there you know but I mean the most important person in the town really speaking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 I meant in the area where you lived.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 No, no one in particular I don't think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What sort of people should shop keepers associate with?
