Well I don't know really, they couldn't afford to fall out with you in those days anyway. No, couldn't afford to fall out with a family you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 There'd be a lot of buying on strap would there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Well I don't know about that, I don't ever reme
mber it being at home, I don't think me mother ever did anything like that. I daresay most - in a lot of cases, yes. But I noticed there was one thing that the - well, in fact it does from being a kid. The Co-operative Society paid a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 dividend}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  and here it w
as three shillings in the pound and they paid it every quarter. Well nearly everybody were Co-op - Co-operative people you know. And they all wanted this money on the day it was paid out. And they didn't want to go for it. So I got the job. I used to go d
o
wn for about four of them, my mother, one or two neighbours, I'd get this divvy and come back I got threepenny bit here, threepenny bit there and a threepenny there - I got a shilling out of it. That was one of my red letter days. I always remember that. 
I
n fact I think I was going down one time and I was a week early. One of the neighbour's said it was due today and I - I didn't know. But I went round and got their books but I was a day early. The clerk said, come next week sonny. Come next week sonny, yo
u'll be all right.
\par 
