e down to talk to me. I'll always think so, as I said a bit since, if I had a hundred thousand pound and two children those two children'd get that hundred thousand pound. You see what I mean. But you get them, same as they have them in Keighley, with a f
i
rm there, Cloughs - or Woodgrow and Haggas's. Cloughs was the Chairman of the Liberal Association. Haggas's were the Chairman of the Conservative Association. And they were both in the same line of business. Their interests were - practically exact. See w
h
at I mean, both the same interest. Both of them were. But - the Haggas's were Conservatives and the Cloughs were Liberals and they are today. They are today. We used to have a - we used to be Clough - Clough Smith and Haggas in Keighley, at least they're 
a
ll on the council, very like - I', not saying that they couldn't be on the council either side because they were; business men. We don't get business men on now. You know, we get a lot of people on now that can't look after their own money. You see what I
 mean. If you have a business man on he has enough up here to look after the money. Usually. And that's what I think about that. And you won't get them go onto the council now to mix with these fellows that get on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Think what - me mother? No, no. No, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 You've suggested that it was possible for people to move up from one social class to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. But you've got to do it yourself you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 By hard work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. You've got to do it yourself, or you never lose those - you never loss those childhood years you know. You never lose them you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did you know anybody who did and who was thoroughly accepted into a higher strata of society?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
Well I'll give you the example of one chap, well - we - there's several professors come out of Keighley you know, Asa Briggs. Professor Asa Briggs, he was one. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What sort of a home did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Just - medium. Just a medium sort of a
 home, he's a very clever fellow. He's got some big government post now. And - Bracewell Smith, he was a teacher. He was a pupil teacher in Keighley, up at Ingrow and he got it into his head that the hotel business was what he wanted. There was business t
h
ere and he threw teaching up and went into it. And he borrowed money from all and sundry you see. Wherever he could get hold of it and he went to London. And he was Bracewell Smith that owns the Park Hotel now, he's been Lord Mayor of London. His son is -
 
Sir Guy Smith, he has the hotel now. The Park Lane Hotel in London you see. He died and left a million and a quarter I believe and here - this here Cliff Castle that we have here, I don't know whether you've seen it or not - he gave that to the town did B
racewell Smith. He bought it and gave it to the town. Now he was one that came from practically nothing - he was a pupil teacher bear in mind, just - little bit upper strata than we were you know - just going to be a teacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Still working class would you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
Yes. Yes. His headmaster - I've played cricket at his headmaster's school sometimes, who was his headmaster, a right decent fellow, and he encouraged Bracewell as well to get on and he made a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 right}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  go of it did Bracewell. He got plenty of mo
ney. But money - you know it's all right but all the same like gambling and everything else, if you win someone else loses. If you get a lot. And - the old - the old argument - can a - can a businessman be honest, you know, there used to be a very old arg
u
ment about that you know, comes up in the papers and all that sort of thing. Well I always said - that a particularly successful business man could not be honest because he takes advantage of somebody. He'd sell at a penny less than what the other fellow 
was doing. You see what I mean, that sort of thing. Oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did Asa Briggs come from the same area as you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 Yes, comes from here, Asa Briggs. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
I can't tell you much about him because he's older than - well older - he isn't older than me. I just forget what job he has now, he has a good job now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 But he came from a similar district?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh yes. Oh yes. Just - medium class. Medium class, yes. And his people could afford to - let him go to the grammar school. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 Won scholarship for the university and that style and they could - with the grants, they could afford to let him stay until he got on top of course.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Do you remember anybody being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Well - I should think Harry Longsdon, Mr Longsdon, he wa
s Mayor of Keighley 1899 - hundred, hundred and one, into a hundred and two. All the Boer War. He was the mayor of Keighley. And he was a big man at the parish church where we used to go as kids to school and that sort of thing. And they always had a grea
t
 respect for him. But he died - absolutely penniless. They had a firm on here, Summerskills, they were machine makers. Well his - his wife was one of the Summerskills, he were in the firm. They got a crowd in during the war - first war - that ruined the w
hole shop. They took all that off of him. It killed him. Really speaking. And he finished up - nothing. In fact one of the fellows from the parish church - was ink }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 Birmingham}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  I believe it was, or somewhere round Birmingham way, in an antique shop I remember
 a silver casket that they'd given to Harry Longsdon on being made a freeman of the borough, it was in the shop for sale. And he bought it. He bought it and gave it to the town. That was a chap that he'd helped to - Harry Longsdon had helped to put where 
he was, and he wasn't wealthy bear in mind. He had enough to buy this here, you know what I mean, had enough sentiment about it because he'd got such a lift from the other man you see. Oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What was it that made you have this respect for him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
Well I - think - in the first place he'd a lot of interest in all the young chaps that got to the Sunday school and he - give them all a job at his works and that sort of thing. And get them into the town hall, he was the Mayor and that sort of thing. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 He did a lot for a lot of them that way and he was very, very good to the soldiers in the Boer War. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
Very good. The - they went out in 1908 I believe it was, the reservists from Keighley, I were only eight year old then bear in mind, I'm only eight, but I remember them going out and I remember some march - he marched round with them. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 He was the Mayor, he marched round with them and they got a send off from the Keighley steps and he was very, very good with them. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
And after the war, in fact, he was imposed on for years after the war. These fellows coming back you know. And he had it - but they knew between them - well we're skint. We haven't price of a drink, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 we\rquote ve}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  nothing. Well we'll go - somebody go and see Harry Longsdon, we'll be all right. Tell him a tale
. They'd tell him a tale, he'd give them half a crown, you know what I mean. Well half a crown and half a dozen of them you know, they'd go on the beer with half a crown you know those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 They imposed on him, he was soft. He should never have bee
n a business man. His father - his father was a parson. His father was a parson. He should have been a parson. He was never a business man. And then I don't think his wife helped him either. I think she got - rather fond of the bottle. It was a great pity
. I liked him better than any of them. And he's - quilted me ear'ole many a time you know. You know what I mean, Sunday school and that sort of thing where I haven't been doing anything - doing something you know what I mean. Keep quiet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes, yes, used to be - only just below - just below.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What did you think of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 He was all right - he was all right was the policeman, yes, never had any bother with him. And I rememb
er - the - - one of the inspectors lived just below one time and I had an elder brother that was thinking of joining - the police force. You see, things weren't very good those days you know, you couldn't get a job same as you can now you know. He was thi
nking of joining the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 police force}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  and - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 Metropolitan}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
 - some police force and - he just went to see this inspector and he did a lot for him, you - in fact I always told this brother of mine that he never appreciated what he'd done for him. He got him an inte
rview, he got him at - to North Allerton to get passed physically, you know, that sort of thing. And then he decided to go to America all at once, a bit of a craze for going to America. So he went to America instead of joining the police force. Oh no, the
y
 were very good. And I - I always remember - going on the street one day and this inspector was walking down and he's a right typical bobby, right flat feet, you know what I mean. He walked very heavy and he - going down - a woman has a line of washing ac
r
oss the road and a chap wanted to come up in a horse and cart to deliver some coal or something right up this street you know what I mean. And he's grumbling about this washing. And this inspector just took his - put his hand in his pocket, pulled out a k
n
ife and cut the line down, he said, that's no right to be across here, he said. Clear it at one side and off you go. But he didn't get a very good name from the lady then. She was a bit - she wasn't going to shift it for him and that sort of thing you kno
w. He settled it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Was your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. Rented.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did you see anything of your landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
Very little. Only when you - pay the rent. We always had to go pay the rent, I've paid it hundreds of times. Me mother would never allow anybod
y calling. For rent or anything like that. No, she didn't like it. She just had her own ways had the old lady you know. But she was good. Didn't take much, you just slip up to the top, it was only about ten minutes walk, pay the rent and down that was fin
ished with.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What was he like as a landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh he was all right. He wasn't bad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Do you remember feeling at the time that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 your mother}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  had really to struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh yes, yes, every - we was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 You were conscious of it at the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
Conscious - conscious of it all the time. And that just got - got you more bitter against your father the whole time because he was the cause of it all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 I suppose his not working for periods would make it ever worse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. Oh 
yes. It was always a struggle, you know what I mean. And you know as you got older - you know what I mean, you thought like from fifteen to twenty, you change your views a little bit you know, things like that. Same as I - when I was about eighteen I got 
t
his share in the mill as an overlooker and instead of working at the usual rate of ten shillings a week I had a pound a week for this job. Well I used to pay my mother sixteen shillings a week out of this pound and keep myself in clothes, I'd only four sh
illings to keep myself in spending money and clothes. That's all I had. But me father never ever out of his pay sixteen shillings a week at home. Never in this world. Never. And you - you just start }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 thinking}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  then. And they wonder why you turn against them. Oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Was it through the children working that your mother was able to manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
That was the only way she could do it, she'd never have sent one of us to the mill if she could have helped it. Never in this world. The eldest - the - that other o
ne - he never went into the mill. I don't think me eldest sister ever did. I'm not just sure on that. But the youngest never went into the mill. You see, we were better off then, we were all grown up and that sort of thing. Oh no, she'd never have let any
 
of us go into the mill if she could have helped it. 'Cos you were rather looked down upon going into the mill then - those - days you know. If you wanted to say anything nasty about anybody you know, these girls when they got to be eighteen, twenty, well 
she's nothing to talk about, she went to work, she went to mill at fourteen year old, you know what I mean, and that sort of thing. Put you down to zero again.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Were you given lessons at all before you went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Eeh no, there's no time. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 How old were you when you first went?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
School? Eeh I don't know, about three. Three or four, I'm not just sure. As soon - as soon as ever we - me mother could get shot of us, yes, off to school. She knew we were all right there. And then there w
as always one older going. To look after you, you know what I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 When you first started what time did you go and what time did you come back, were the school hours pretty much as they are now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Well - well - nine o'clock 'til twelve was it about. Half past one, quarter to two to four o'clock something like or quarter past.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did you go all day when you were three?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes I think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 You didn't go for just half a day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh no, they could do but me mother wouldn't have it. She wouldn't - stop at school all day, stop at school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What kind of a school was it, was it a board school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 No, the church - church school. Church school, Church of England, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Mixed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. Yes, yes, it was a mixed, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Boys and girls were taught in one class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. Yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Was it fairly near, how did you get there, how long did it take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 It was - take us ten minutes. Ten minutes easily.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 A ten minute walk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Was it an older brother or sister who took you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 You went home for your midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh well, didn't think much about it, I didn't bother. Oh all right, yes, it was all right, yes, I got on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
Well not too bad. Not too badly, they've got a job to do, you know what I mean, and you know that they're - they're there to keep you in the place sort of style and try and teach you something. Oh yes, we always respected them and all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Were there any that you specially liked or disliked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 No I don't think so. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did they emphasise certain things like manners or tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh yes, they - yes, they tried to keep you that way, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Was punctuality important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What about the way you spoke, were they concerned about that at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Well I don't think they were - not in my case anyway. Perhaps there was some - plenty of the others that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 spoke}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  worse than what I did you know, have more to do with them than - didn't bother me much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 If you did something that the teachers disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Well when you were young - put you in a corner maybe, something like that. As you older - come over t
he old whatsit he'd give you a flip on your nose or something like that you know. If you got five or six you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What about caning?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. Yes, I've been caned, yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What sort of offences would you get the different sorts of punishments for? Did the severity increase with age or with the nature of the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 offence}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
Yes. No, with age I think. Because if you got it as a youngster if you were something small you always remembered it you know what I mean, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Were the girls punished in the same way as boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
No, I don't think so, I couldn't say, I don't know what they did with them. Give them a good talking to as much as anything I think. They couldn't do a right lot could they, they couldn't sort - of cane them as kids.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Was there much punishment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 No. No, not a lot, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork, did your mother ask you what you'd been doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. Something like - yes, probably, yes. Some of the elder ones would do you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did your mother ever visit the school or meet any of the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 No. No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. Yes. Very similar. Sometimes some rather - better class. 'Cos they used to p
ut in a few years here then - send them to the grammar school. They could afford to pay for them to go to grammar school you see. You could get in the grammar school by paying.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did the teachers single out some of the children for special treatment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
Well I think if they showed a bit of brilliance, yes, because have a bit more intelligence. Of course I always think that the teachers were always alike, they wanted these children to go in and pass certain exams, get scholarships and they got the cred
it for it you see. Oh yes, they were all right that way. Of course there were some of them you couldn't have - you couldn't have knocked it in with a hammer never mind anything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Well when you got up a bit, yes. When you got eight, ten year old, you know, something of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Were there any children who were left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Not often. Not often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 How long did you stay at the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 I stayed 'til I had to go to - to work. I was there somewhere seven or eight years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 How old were you when you became a half timer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
I think it was eleven years of age. About eleven or twelve, I think it was eleven and I became full timer when I was twelve, I think that was it. If not it was twelve and thirteen but I think it was eleven and twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Would you have stayed longer if you could have done, would you have liked to have gone on to the grammar school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Well I - I think I would. But you always had it in mind that - they w
ere always short at home and there had to be someone to bring a little bit more in. If you went into the factory you were just bringing a little more in. You had - you'd to look at - to look at it both way you know. In fact - the mother used to decide tha
t. You know what I mean, she'd say, well I can't afford to do it, can't afford to let you go to grammar school, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 you\rquote ll}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
 want more clothes, you'll want everything to keep up with them, well I can't afford to do it, we haven't the money. Therefore that was what happened.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 But you went on to the evening classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 That was a spinning course was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 City and guilds, something of that kind was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Well that was the exam you took, yes, later, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
What now? Well I'm too old to have any regrets that's worthwhile. I've got too old to bother about it either. No I don't think so. Oh I' admit that when you get into - certain company sometime you feel a little bit - 
backward. What I mean to say, the public schoolboy, you can tell him wherever you go can't you. You can tell him wherever you go, university man and that sort of thing. You can always tell them but you always feel - whenever - whatever position, you know,
 I've worked with them, you know what I mean, I've played with them and all that sort of thing but they've always that little bit - on you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 That little bit of polish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh yes.
 Oh yes. Yes. Yes, the evening classes particularly. Because it's got - some of the teachers there you know were - mill managers and that sort of thing you see and if there's - if there some lad was making a bit of progress they'd give him a bit of encour
agement and if you went for a job and you asked him for a reference he'd give you a good one. He'd give you a nice reference. Oh yes, he used to help you a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 The year that you were a half timer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Apart from the fact of your teachers n
ot showing any personal interest in you, do you think you benefited from it at all educationally or was it completely wasted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What that half - wasted. Wasted - might as well have let me - go to the factory for the whole day. It'd have been better both ways.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 When you started as a half timer what exactly were you doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
Well do you understand - have you been in a mill? You see the spinning mills have you? Well when the bobbins are full they've to be taken off and then empty one put on. We used to do that job. To begin with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 This was a wool spinning mill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 A - yes. A wool spinning mill. And they had long rails where they keep your empty }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 bobbins}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  you know and you simply take a full }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 bobbin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  off her and put an empty one here. And then ther
e's a lad has to come and take the full bobbins off and another one has to come and set them again, there were little jobs like that you see. Then oiling the machines and all that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 A sort of jobber as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh yes. Yes, that's right. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Were you doing that sort of thing all the time that you were a half timer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
Oh - well when I was full timer, when you left, you couldn't get much further when you left, at fourteen or fifteen. Then when you went about fifteen yo
u'd be ready for a trade in those days then. You had to go for a trade, you'd to serve six years apprenticeship for a trade then. But up to then you'd be doing odd job. Well I went in for overlooking in the mills, you see what I mean, then I got taken off
 those jobs and had to start walking about being the overlooker, you see what I mean, and - well learning to process it you see, these big processes but you don't know how it's done. You've got to learn them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 How did you get the job as a half timer in the first place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh the - well one of ours - one us at the mill at the time and he asked the overlooker. He asked the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 overlooker}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  if he wanted one and we had to wait. Yes, your job wasn't around, you know what I mean, you have to - have to wait for yo
ur month before you got in you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did you have any holidays at all as a half timer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What - away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did you have any holiday from work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. Two days - same as was all the time. Two days at Christmas, two days at Easter, two days at W
hitsuntide and three days at parish feast. That was the holidays you got. No more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 These were unpaid holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh yes. You never got paid for those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 How did your employer treat you as a half timer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Well very good. They're very good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did you like him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes, you just did your work - just did your work and they never trouble you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What did you feel about the work, did you like it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 All right. I did - I got rather interested in it - well as I say, I took it on after you see and went into it. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did the job alter your attitude to school that last year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
May I don't know that it did. I - I were more interested in the mill then, you know what I mean, than school. I used to think these fellows were very fortunate as I knew they'd be eighteen and twenty before they start - earning a living a lot of them. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 I think that they're very, very fortunate if they only knew it.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 From being a half timer you started full time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 In the same place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Same place, oh yes, the same place, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 You'd then worked the full time hours - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 fifty five}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 a half}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  hour week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Fifty-five and a half hour week, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 How did the pattern of your work change then, you went on then to serve an apprenticeship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 How long was that for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Well I wasn't really - indented for it - at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 More a training period was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 That's right, I went from a boy - I got used to it and then I got put into a small shed of machines. And
 ordinary overlooker shall we say he had twenty machines to look after. There'd be a share come up - perhaps they were putting new machine in or something like that, and there'd be about four or five machines. I got put into one of those, you see what I m
ean. To }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 begin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
 with. And then as I went on I increased and increased you see as I went along. Oh yes, it was - that was all right, it was a good part of it. Because I was - I was rather fortunate because they were starting a new mill and I was junior apprent
ice there and there were three stories, well there were four really, but there were three stories, well there were four really, but there were three big spinning rooms to this mill, and one was one type of spinning, one was another and one was another. Th
r
ee different types you see. And of course the - they were putting this new machinery in and whichever room were busiest were going on I had to go in, I was the mug for three rooms, and you understand I thought I was a mug but I found our since that it was
 
a bit of darned good training. I got some right good training you see what I mean. In the ordinary course of events I should never have had. I got - and you get a bit of confidence when you can go into one room and then into another and into another and t
a
ke it on. I did that until I became twenty-one, then I was a man. Then you got a man's wages then which wasn't a right lot then. It was what - twenty-eight shillings a week I believe. And we at our firm had a bonus system. And we could earn - about four s
hillings a week.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 How did that work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 The amount you got off. The amount that - production. Your production bonus.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 How did this share business operate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Well - it depends really - some shares are quite a lot easier than others. All - in 
those days all these mills here had a certain - what we used to call bread and butter lines. Used to make one type of yarn for a certain thing. One type of yarn for this, linings or anything that came with you know. Well you get onto some machines there t
h
at - you wouldn't have to change them, they'd go for twelve months at a time without being changed, you see. Now they were easy to man you see you've got to keep your machine in good condition and keep walking round and see it was all right. Then when you
 get on - they have - into one place you'll }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 have}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
 half a dozen - ten different kinds of yarn to make, you see what I mean. Well their always changing it. They always change for different types, you see what I mean, and it makes it a lot harder work. And that
's how you come in - you get your - bread and butter jobs first and particularly after the war started in 1914 everything went onto khaki immediately you know. That was a bit change for a chap like me, I'd never done any coloured before, always white. Dif
ferent - qualities of white you know, wool is rather fickle, you get }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 wool}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
 with fibres so long you know and you'll get it with fibres so long. Well they take bit of - there's a lot different treatment with this to that, you understand, in the setting of your
 machines. And - when the war broke out and I say all the khaki you're thrown out altogether, you see what I mean, you're straight away - of course week or two you tot used to it and knew what it was and then again that - that was another bread and butter
 job. You put a whole mill onto khaki and nothing else. Simply making }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 khaki}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  yarns you know for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 soldiers\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  clothes and sort of thing. Well it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 isn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  really hard work isn't that. It's more super - it's more overlooking, supervising than what it is - actual working. So long as you get your settings right to begin with you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 The share meant the particular apportions of the machines that you were responsible for?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Exactly. Yes, exactly, precisely, that is right. That's right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 It didn't have any financial implications?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
No, no. They had these shares, you know what I mean, they had it - and they knew everything that was being made on those machines. If any complaints about them they could go straight to the machine where it had been made. Then
 you were for the jump then you see what I mean. They had it done that way. But the finance side they did all that. The bosses did all that. You couldn't tell who did that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 How long did you stay at the mill as an overlooker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 'Til I went soldieri
ng. 'Til I went soldiering. I went soldiering during the war. I was two years there. Then I came back, and I was overlooking then - oh - let me see, about five - well nearly ten years after that, overlooking. I'd be overlooking - at different places. I le
ft the place where I was. I went to different mills. You see, I had a varied experience that way. And then I got the managing job - managing a mill in 1940. That was the best move I made you see, what I mean. That -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Was that still a spinning mill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
It - the Lowe Mills - do you know where the station is at Keighley? Just by the station. The street before you come to the station, down there there's a big mill on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 right hand}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  side. I used to manage that. And of course that - that was a big move, you
 see, because you did everything, you're drawing, you're spinning, twisting, you're winding, you're reeling - everything. You say - if fact they had combing down there - I had nothing to do with the combing. Where they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 comb}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  the wool in, you see what I mean
, sort it, wash it, comb it and it comes to us and it goes out as a wool, making a warp for the weaver, you know what a warp is don't you. That was the best - that was the best move I'd make up to then. And I was there '40 - I left there in '50 and I went
 to Greece in '50. I took a plant out to Greece. A plant of spinning machinery. And I stuck it there seven year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Was this for a firm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 For a Greek firm. For a Greek firm. I was - I got the job through the Pinksmiths here, the makers. The chap - th
ey came to see me about it, he knew these people very well, he knew the financial position, he knew what they were talking about and he just - because like at that time. I had a good wage then, I daresay, I'd be the highest paid manager in Keighley, or ve
ry near, maybe one or two, but very near. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 And I chucked that up to take this job, 'course it took a bit of deciding, that was to sell a house, sell up and go out there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 But I went out there and I stayed there - I started this plant and I stayed there seven 
years. I had a right good do. And I - at the end of seven years I was sixty-five, I was pensionable. But I'd been home every other year when I was out there, I got - I had to come every - every other year. Paid }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 expenses}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  and that sort of thing. I went back 
and I did another two years. No, I went for five years first, that was right, and then I did two years after, the fifty strike. Because I thought the cost of living was going up so much here, which it was, I reckon that in those days the cost of living wa
s going up five }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 percent}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
 a year, at least, it is yet of course. Like - wanted a bit of compensation for that you see. And I was young enough, I could manage and I had an easy - had an easy job there, I knew what it was. So I stayed another two years. See wha
t I mean. Then I finished.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 You were managing this plant out there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 I was managing it - oh yes, yes. Oh yes, a splendid job. Grand job was that. They just gave you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 ,you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  see what I mean, they gave you a - certain type of yarn to make that they'd 
been buying in Bradford. And they were the best spinners in Bradford, this is what you have to go like. And I said now then if you want this type of yarn you'd better buy the type }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 of}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748  wool that'll do it, we'll see that you've no need to worry about that and
 keep it up. And they did do all right. And I haven't the slightest. I simply got it going and I sent samples here, they wanted samples sending to the firm where he'd been buying his yarn to see - ask them to analyse it, examine it and see if it was good 
as what they did. And I also got a parcel of it to send to the conditioning house in Bradford, which is - the legal standard of anything in the wool connection then you know. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 
And he sent to body places and got a very, very good report from both places. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Afte
r that, not the slightest trouble. And I had no more machinery to mind there than I had when I was eighteen year old. No more. Than I - when I was eighteen year old. And I'd three overlookers for the day turn and three overlookers for the night turn. I'm 
s
aying the night turn, six o'clock in the morning 'til two and then two 'til ten. And we used to have sixteen hours a day and I've six overlookers to look after. And I just walk about. If I wanted a day off to go anywhere, I went. I had a car to go with. I
 could do just what I wanted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 I didn't ask you about shift work in the mill here, was there any in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh well - at that time, no. No. No, there wasn't any in the early days. It was all steady like that. Not here. In the - in Bradford the
y used to do a lot and the combing mills used to do a lot. The coming mills always run a night shift. 'Course the combers always said that if they didn't run a night turn they couldn't make it pay. You see, they're overheads are the same, night and day, j
u
st the same. Night - you see, they run a night turn a lot cheaper than they are the day turn, and they can afford to pay a little bit more money for them to work at nights. That's the reason they all do it now you know. They're all on - night turn, they w
o
rk night turns, 'course all the - a lot of the spinning are working nights now because things are so busy. And then again a lot of them haven't got all the plant running, they haven't - you haven't enough work people to do all the plant - to run all the p
lant. You get it that way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Would you have preferred another type of occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
I don't think so. No, I used to think I was tired but when I got - you know, as you're going through life, if you're five pound a week for a job and you've another o
ne comes up at eight pound a week and you get - it's a different life altogether. That three pound a week makes a lot of difference. To an ordinary man. To an ordinary man it makes a lot of difference you know. And - as I got on and I used to - well I cou
l
d just save a bit you know what I mean, when I got this managing job which was of course considerably better and then I go to Greece and I'm better still. I went to Greece I'd - I'd more money than I have here. A lot more. And I've no income tax to pay. A
nd I had it paid in England. You see what I mean, I - just watched my p's and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 q's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
 a bit, you know what I mean. It takes a bit of doing when you're in these foreign countries you know because you can. And I just got enough there to live on if I - I got as mu
ch there I can live off the same money on it there. But we had seven real good years in Greece. No - no regrets all about Greece. Have you ever been? It's the most beautiful country in the world.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did you belong to any trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Or professional organisation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
No. No. No. No. I always thought - I might have been a bit - clever, I don't know, I always thought I could look after myself. I'd rather go and ask a boss for a rise than tell trade union, be told by the shop steward that we
're going in for a rise, if we don't get it we're coming out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did you feel that employers and workers had the same outlook in the early days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 No, I don't think - I don't know. Oh no, the outlooks' - if you've got that much money the outlook - yo
ur outlook's different altogether. There's no, you see, a big difference between leaving here and going to Greece. Now there's only two classes in Greece. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 
That's the top class and the bottom. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Know what I mean, there's no medium, there's no medium there. An
d you have the - the bottom class, they live off bread and water or - grapes and all that sort of thing they grow themselves, you know what I mean, grapes and bucketsful of them. Well they - they live off these things, you know, they live very cheap. They
 don't have - well if you had meat twice a week in Greece they'd think you were a top notcher. And if you went out and had steak and chips tonight well I don't know what they'd think about you. Think you're a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 millionaire}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 . But you can get it there, understand it's there for the people that can afford it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Back - in your early days in the mill did you feel that there were divisions of interest amongst the workers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Well - I daresay in the first place, yes. But - you know what I mean - you could have 
an opinion on these things and that sort of thing you couldn't afford to express them. You couldn't afford - you daren't. You daren't - everybody was frightened of their job in those days you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did you feel that there was a big division between trained craftsmen and other workers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Not as much, no. No. Not as I thought, no. But a sooner the wage the trained craftsman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Would you say that starting work full time changed your attitude to live?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh yes, I thought I were a man then. Yes, I was taking something home, you know what I mean. I was - I was doing something like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did it change your relationship with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Oh no. Not - not with me mother. No. Not with me mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 What about with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 
Oh no, they thought about - they were all right, they were going on their own way. I'd a brother a pattern maker, another one a plumber. Well you see in their case they had to work 'til fifteen to twenty-one for about five up to ten shillings a week ne
arly over five years. You see, I hadn't that. I was a bit more fortunate but of course - it had to go into the home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did you spend your Sundays any differently after you started full time work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1986840 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Did you go on going to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16464440 NP  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5328074\charrsid11084748 Yes. Yes, just as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1342632\charrsid11084748 usual}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
